Brandeis University Worcester Polytechnic Institute
- MIMIC-III noteevents table - discharge summaries.
- 58K ICU patients free-text clinical notes.
- Discarded records with rare diagnoses (<50 records).
-Wikipedia pages of diagnoses used as KBs (first paragraph and 'Signs and Symptoms' section).
- Wiki page titles are values and page content is key.
- Convert the input (x) to internal representation
- Learn embeddings (BOW/GRU/LSTM)
- Use pretrained vectors (GLOVE/W2V)
- Make memory state (u), write initial data to the memory
-Update when necessary
- Generate the output state, which is a combination of memory state and input
- Convert the output (O) into response as desired by the model

Training
- Distribution of diagnoses has long tail.
- We found 4186 unique diagnoses but most occur only once.
- 50 most common diagnoses cover 97% of the notes.
- 100 most common diagnoses covers 99.97% of the notes.
- We used maximum of 600 words in notes and wiki-pages.
- Vocabulary size was fixed to 20K. Embedding dimension was 500.
- Adam was used for optimization with learning rate of 0.001; batch size was 100.
- Loss is sum of cross entropy from prediction labels and prediction of memory slots.
- L2 loss and dropout of 0.5 used for regularization.
Metrics
- AUC calculated by taking unweighted mean of AUC values.
- Average Precision is reported over top five predictions.
- Hamming loss is reported instead of accuracy because of multi-label classification.
- All results are from 10% of withheld test set after training for 100 Epochs.
Analysis
- Our model outperforms other variants of memory networks.
- Difference in performance is more pronounced at higher hops.
- A-MemNN which does not add any extra parameters also performs better at higher hops.
- Across all models, higher hops is always better with diminishing return.
- C-MemNN has 30% more parameters compared to standard memory networks.
- Training loss plot (->) shows more parameters in our model does not lead to overfitting.
- Because of parallel update of condensed memory state, inference time is same across models.
